Scrape/Extract Fortune 500 Table¶

In [2]:
# Use Pandas to scrape the table containing stocks data.
url_stock = "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_S%26P_500_companies"

# Convert table to html
stock_table = pd.read_html(url_stock)

# Print table 
print(stock_table)

Type of Data & Convert to DataFrame¶

In [3]:
# Identify what type is the output data
type(stock_table)

# Ensure to select the first part of the list
stock_table_df = pd.DataFrame(stock_table[0])

# Save raw data to csv
stock_table_df.to_csv("../stocks_data/raw_fortune500table.csv", index=False, encoding='utf8')

stock_table_df.head()

Extract Daily Stocks Data for fortune 500¶

In [5]:
base_url = "https://cloud.iexapis.com/stable/stock/"
key_token = "/quote?token=pk_e4c3fa15e49a4efca388fcfbcece0eac"

# Empty list to store data
stocks_data = []

# Start counter for the loop

symbol_counter = 1

#symbols_list2 = ['MMM','ABT','AIG','HAL','SLB'] # test list

#Print statement to inform when data acquisition start
print(f"Beginning Data Acquisition!!!")
print(f"------------&&&&-------------------")

for symbol in tqdm(symbols_list): #Note that we are using the symbol list
    try: 
        response = requests.get(base_url+symbol+key_token).json()
        stocks_data.append(response)
        
        print(f"Data Acquisition {symbol_counter} | Stock Symbol : {symbol}")
        symbol_counter = symbol_counter + 1
    except:
        print("Stock not found...!!")
    continue
    
# Print statement to inform when all records have been acquired.
print(f"------------&&&&---------------")
print(f"Data Acquisition Complete")
print(f"------------&&&&---------------")

Extract Historical Stocks Data¶

Stocks Price & Dividend - Financial Services - Insurance¶

In [8]:
# Yahoo Finance API

historical_url = "https://apidojo-yahoo-finance-v1.p.rapidapi.com/stock/v2/get-historical-data"

headers = {
    'x-rapidapi-host': "apidojo-yahoo-finance-v1.p.rapidapi.com",
    'x-rapidapi-key': "09ec0160admsh2d5563a7feaa3efp1e2db5jsn5787845ed7fc"
    }

prices_list = []
event_list = []

stock_history_counter = 1

# List of 20 Stocks from Insurance industry

symbols_insurance = ['AIG','AFL','ALL','AON','AJG','CB','CINF','RE','GL','HIG','MMC','MET','PFG','PGR','PRU','TRV','UNM','WLTW','LNC','L']

# symbols_insurance = ['AIG','AFL','ALL'] # Test list

#Print statement to inform when data acquisition start
print(f"Beginning Data Acquisition!!!")
print(f"------------&&&&-------------------")

for s in tqdm(symbols_insurance):
    
    querystring = {"frequency":"1wk","filter":"history","period1":"1136219674","period2":"1567528474","symbol": s}

    try: 
        response_history = requests.get(historical_url,headers = headers, params=querystring).json()
        
        prices = response_history['prices']
        events = response_history['eventsData']
        
        for price in prices:
            price['symbol'] = s
            prices_list.append(price)
        
        for event in events:
            event['symbol'] = s
            event_list.append(event)
        
        print(f"Data Acquisition {stock_history_counter} | Stock Symbol : {s}")
        
        stock_history_counter = stock_history_counter+ 1
    
    except:
        print("Stock not found...!!")
    continue
    
# Print statement to inform when all records have been acquired.
print(f"------------&&&&---------------")
print(f"Data Acquisition Complete")
print(f"------------&&&&---------------")

Extract News Stock Data - Financial Services - Insurance¶

Daily News Stocks - Financial Services - Insurance¶

In [12]:
# Yahoo Finance API - News Data

news_url = "https://apidojo-yahoo-finance-v1.p.rapidapi.com/stock/get-news"


#symbols_insurance = ['AIG','AFL','ALL'] # testing list
symbols_insurance = ['AIG','AFL','ALL','AON','AJG','CB','CINF','RE','GL','HIG','MMC','MET','PFG','PGR','PRU','TRV','UNM','WLTW','LNC','L']


headers = {
    'x-rapidapi-host': "apidojo-yahoo-finance-v1.p.rapidapi.com",
    'x-rapidapi-key': "09ec0160admsh2d5563a7feaa3efp1e2db5jsn5787845ed7fc"
    }

stocks_news = []

stock_news_counter = 1

#Print statement to inform when data acquisition start
print(f"Beginning Data Acquisition!!!")
print(f"------------&&&&-------------------")

for news in tqdm(symbols_insurance):

    querystring_news = {"region":"US","category":news}

    try: 
        response_news = requests.get(news_url,headers = headers, params= querystring_news).json()
        
        stocks_news.append(response_news)
           
        print(f"Data Acquisition {stock_news_counter} | Stock Symbol : {news}")
        
        stock_news_counter = stock_news_counter + 1
    
    except:
        print("Stock not found...!!")
    continue
    
# Print statement to inform when all records have been acquired.
print(f"------------&&&&---------------")
print(f"Data Acquisition Complete")
print(f"------------&&&&---------------")

stocks_news_list = []

for i in range(len(stocks_news)):
    for j in range(len(stocks_news[i]['items']['result'])):
        stocks_news_list.append(stocks_news[i]['items']['result'][j])
        #ticker_list.append(stocks_news[i]['items']['result'][j]['entities'])

  'content': '<p>By Suzanne Barlyn</p> \n<p>NEW YORK (Reuters) - Bruce Gendelman wanted a mountainside retreat when he bought 12 acres in Aspen, Colorado. But forest fires that have torched nearby land in recent years left him concerned.</p> \n<p>So Gendelman, who runs an insurance brokerage, tapped into a program that American International Group Inc offers to help design luxury properties in ways that mitigate disaster risk. A risk specialist made sure his home had a lightning-repellant system, cisterns to hold water run-off and ceramic shingles that look like wood. Just in case a blaze does break out, his driveway was designed to accommodate a fire truck\'s maneuvers.</p> \n<p>"It\'s a very high-end home and we\'re dealing with very good contractors," Gendelman said. "But (the AIG program) brought them systems they never used and resources they never heard of."</p> \n<p>Fires, floods, hurricanes and other catastrophes have cost https://tmsnrt.rs/2Zq5hUs U.S. insurers more than $170 billion in property losses since 2016, according to Property Claim Services (PCS), part of Verisk Analytics Inc, and the U.S. Bureau of Economic Analysis.</p> \n<p>Few actuaries expect the trend to ease as climate change accelerates, and the swell of claims has prompted some insurers to get involved in the design process for lavish residential properties.</p> \n<p>Insurers and industry groups said they do not track data on the service, which is still a tiny part of the property-casualty insurance industry. But executives, real-estate developers and brokers, builders and analysts who spoke to Reuters said they believe it will only expand.</p> \n<p>"People don\'t naturally think of insurance as the first place to go," said Jennifer Naughton, head of North American personal insurance risk consulting services at Chubb Ltd. "But an insurance company can give you an advantage of the loss potential and might save you the pain of loss in the future."</p> \n<p>Chubb\'s risk managers make sure homeowners who request the service have water storage on the property to supplement the local fire department\'s resources, and recommend devices that allow emergency workers to open electronic entry gates, among other measures.</p> \n<p>The trend is not entirely new: PURE Insurance has offered the service since its founding in 2007, and others have quietly made risk specialists available to customers who are designing a home and know to ask for the service. But it is now picking up steam as a stand-alone business at some major property-casualty insurers, as more clients worry about extreme weather.</p> \n<p>AIG started marketing its service as "Smart Build" in 2015. Initially, only residential construction projects that cost more than $5 million were eligible, but AIG lowered the threshold to $1 million two years later.</p> \n<p>AIG would not say how many homes it has helped design in total, but a spokesman said there were 20% more projects enrolled during the first six months of 2019 than in the prior-year period.</p> \n<p>Cincinnati Insurance Companies joined the fray more recently, as did Vault, a high net-worth insurer launched in 2017 by a group of former AIG executives. W.R. Berkley Corp is also looking to offer the service as it ramps up business with wealthy clientele.</p> \n<p> </p>\n<p>(GRAPHIC on property losses due to U.S. disasters link: https://fingfx.thomsonreuters.com/gfx/editorcharts/INSURERS-DISASTERS/0H001QERS818/index.html)</p> \n<p> </p>\n<p>FINE ART PROTECTION</p> \n<p>The home design process typically begins with an insurance risk specialist scoping out a site to assess possible dangers. For instance, if there is a high water table underground or a nearby body of water, they may suggest elevating the home or choosing another place to build to avoid the risk of flooding.</p> \n<p>Ken Vona, who heads KVC Builders LLC and frequently teams up with PURE, recalled a couple who decided against a location because the house would have to be raised some 18 feet (5.5 m)off the ground to guard against flood risk. </p> \n<p>"A perfect example of \'bad piece of property, nice view,\'" he said.</p> \n<p>Once a site is selected, specialists review architectural plans, making sure designs are resistant to water and fire damage, among other risks. They scrutinize plumbing layouts, help design hurricane-proof storage rooms to protect valuables, vet the adequacy of sprinkler systems, measure driveway entrances and make sure there is a hydrant nearby.</p> \n<p>Cameron Strothman, a senior risk manager for AIG Private Client Group, said he once had to figure out how to protect a site that was four miles away from the nearest hydrant. He liaised with the local fire department and advised the client to install a 30,000-gallon tank under the driveway so that fire trucks could tap a private water source instead. It cost $35,000.</p> \n<p>Risk specialists\' suggestions generally represent 10 to 15% of total building costs, insurance experts said.</p> \n<p>Some of the features are things homebuilders would likely install anyway, like a sophisticated fire alarm or sprinkler system, or measures required by building codes. Others cost very little money but can prevent extremely expensive damage. For instance, there is a $100 sensor that shuts off water systems after detecting a leak.</p> \n<p>Adding these features at the time of construction is also cheaper than doing so once the home is built, risk experts said. A protective storage room for fine art may run less than $100,000 if designed into the plans compared to millions of dollars later, said Steve Bitterman, Vault\'s chief risk services officer.</p> \n<p>Gendelman would not disclose the costs associated with building or protecting his home, but said AIG did not charge him for the advice.</p> \n<p>"Providing this service free is smart for everyone," he said. "They help me with ideas and they get a loyal client."</p> \n<p> </p>\n<p> (Reporting by Suzanne Barlyn, Editing by Rosalba O\'Brien)</p>',

  'content': '<p></p>\n<p><b>Activities Reflect Company\'s 24-Year, <span class="xn-money">$136</span>-plus Million Commitment to Childhood Cancer Initiatives</b></p> \n<p><span class="xn-location">COLUMBUS, Ga.</span>, <span class="xn-chron">Sept. 3, 2019</span> /PRNewswire/ -- Aflac, the leader in supplemental insurance sales at U.S. worksites, will commemorate National Childhood Cancer Awareness Month this September with a full slate of actions and activities designed to raise awareness and help provide comfort for those impacted by childhood cancer. The monthlong tribute includes multiple activations as well as special grants to enhance programs nationwide that provide comfort and support to pediatric cancer patients and their siblings. </p> \n<p>"When Aflac began its commitment to childhood cancer research and treatment in 1995 by establishing the Aflac Cancer and Blood Disorders Center at Children\'s Healthcare of <span class="xn-location">Atlanta</span>, we knew that we, as a company, needed to help children and families going through this terrible challenge," Aflac Chairman and CEO <span class="xn-person">Dan Amos</span> said. "What we didn\'t know is the profound impact it would have on our company, our employees and our independent sales agents who contribute more than <span class="xn-money">$6 million</span> from their commission checks each year. It has been an inspirational and true calling for the entire Aflac family."</p> \n<p>"National Childhood Cancer Awareness Month is a special time at Aflac, as it gives us an opportunity to pause and contemplate how far we have come in supporting children and families impacted by cancer. At the same time, we are reminded that continued support of research and discovery is critical to the defeat of these diseases,"&nbsp;said The Aflac Foundation, Inc. President <span class="xn-person">Kathelen Amos</span>. "Aflac\'s culture and mission is to help people during their greatest times of need, so we will continue to raise awareness, comfort families and contribute valuable resources for the treatment and research of childhood cancer until the day comes where every child has a full lifetime."</p> \n<p>Among the September activities, The Aflac Childhood Cancer Foundation, Inc. will award five <span class="xn-money">$2,000</span> grants to child life programs at hospitals across the country that treat children with cancer. Hospitals will use the funding for initiatives such as developing an isolation playroom and pediatric oncology family support programs, offering yoga for patients and families, and developing support programs designed for siblings of patients who have passed away. The Foundation plans to make these annual grants, allowing for five different recipients each year.</p> \n<p>Other initiatives scheduled for National Childhood Cancer Awareness Month and beyond include:</p> \n<ul type="disc">\n <li><b><span class="xn-chron">Sept. 18, 2019</span></b>: Aflac will deliver its innovative My Special Aflac Duck<sup></sup> to patients at the Children\'s Hospital of <span class="xn-location">Philadelphia</span> during a special duck delivery event. <i>My Special Aflac Duck</i>, designed by <a target="_blank" href="https://c212.net/c/link/?t=0&amp;l=en&amp;o=2567960-1&amp;h=2842242928&amp;u=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.sproutel.com%2F&amp;a=Sproutel" rel="nofollow">Sproutel</a>, is a social robot that uses medical play, lifelike movement, and emotions to engage and help comfort kids during their cancer care. Aflac has delivered more than 5,000 <i>My Special Aflac Ducks</i> since its introduction last October. To date, more than 220 hospitals in 47 states across the country have received <i>My Special Aflac Ducks</i> from Aflac for their pediatric cancer patients, completely free of charge. </li>\n <li><b><span class="xn-chron">Sept. 23, 2019</span></b>: Aflac will release its annual Corporate Social Responsibility Report, available at Aflac.com/CSRReport. The report highlights how Aflac employees and partners drive positive impact in their communities. It also honors specific CSR heroes around the country, including <span class="xn-person">Lindsay Carrick</span>, a child life specialist at the Aflac Cancer and Blood Disorders Center of Children\'s Healthcare of <span class="xn-location">Atlanta</span>. Carrick is a real-life hero whose relentless dedication to her patients provides a greater sense of control in their lives and comfort and joy during their cancer treatment. </li>\n <li><b><span class="xn-chron">Sept. 25, 2019</span></b>: Aflac and <span class="xn-person">Chispa House</span>, a documentary film crew from <span class="xn-location">Athens, Georgia</span>, will hold the worldwide premiere of the powerful new film <a target="_blank" href="https://c212.net/c/link/?t=0&amp;l=en&amp;o=2567960-1&amp;h=2144551314&amp;u=https%3A%2F%2Fvimeopro.com%2Fproductionsdt%2Fmoments-of-joy-trailer-1&amp;a=%22Moments+of+Joy%22" rel="nofollow">"Moments of Joy"</a> at The Atlantic Festival in <span class="xn-location">Washington, D.C.</span> The film provides a glimpse into the emotional challenges and celebrated moments along the pediatric cancer journey through the eyes and words of children, families and caregivers. Follow @AtlanticLIVE on social media for more information as the premiere event approaches. </li>\n <li><b>Through the end of October</b>, Aflac and Macy\'s are introducing a new, limited-edition plush Childhood Cancer Awareness Duck, which honors the medical professionals who support these courageous children. Sold exclusively on <a target="_blank" href="https://c212.net/c/link/?t=0&amp;l=en&amp;o=2567960-1&amp;h=865238477&amp;u=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.macys.com%2Faflac&amp;a=macys.com%2FAflac" rel="nofollow">macys.com/Aflac</a> and at participating Macy\'s stores, the 6-inch plush duck sells for <span class="xn-money">$10</span>, with 100% of net proceeds going to The Aflac Foundation, Inc. to benefit pediatric cancer programs at participating hospitals around the country. The newest plush wears green scrubs and a scrubs hat in honor of the health care teams who provide care, comfort and hope to pediatric cancer patients daily. When given a squeeze, the duck quacks "Aflaaac!" Shoppers can also get involved by purchasing new, limited-edition gear from AflacChildhoodCancer.org, including a Sherpa blanket, socks, caps and bags, with net proceeds going to support The Aflac Foundation, Inc.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>"Aflac\'s <span class="xn-money">$3 million</span> per year investment in <i>My Special Aflac Duck</i>, as well as our ongoing contributions to childhood cancer initiatives at the Aflac Cancer Center, signify the authenticity of our commitment to being a socially responsible company that cares about the community and individuals," <span class="xn-person">Aflac</span> Senior Vice President and Chief Environmental, Social and Governance (ESG) and Communications Officer <span class="xn-person">Catherine Hernandez-Blades</span> said. "We are excited to demonstrate our dedication to this important national concern through grants, a special duck delivery, honoring our own heroes and premiering an incredibly emotional film that showcases the impact we can all have on such a significant cause."</p> \n<p>To learn more about these programs and Aflac\'s commitment to pediatric cancer research and treatment, visit AflacChildhoodCancer.org.</p> \n<p><b>About Aflac Incorporated <br /></b>Aflac Incorporated (<a href="/q?s=afl">AFL</a>) is a Fortune 500 company helping provide protection to more than 50 million people through its subsidiaries in <span class="xn-location">Japan</span> and the U.S., where it is a leading supplemental insurer, by paying cash fast when policyholders get sick or injured. For more than six decades, insurance policies of Aflac Incorporated\'s subsidiaries have given policyholders the opportunity to focus on recovery, not financial stress. Aflac Life Insurance Japan is the leading provider of medical and cancer insurance in <span class="xn-location">Japan</span>, where it insures 1 in 4 households. Through its trailblazing One Day Pay<sup>SM</sup> initiative in <span class="xn-location">the United States</span>, for eligible claims, Aflac can process, approve and electronically send funds to claimants for quick access to cash in just one business day. For 13 consecutive years, Aflac has been recognized by Ethisphere as one of the World\'s Most Ethical Companies. In 2018, Fortune magazine recognized Aflac as one of the 100 Best Companies to Work for in America for the 20th consecutive year, and in 2019, Fortune included Aflac on its list of World\'s Most Admired Companies for the 18th time. To find out more about One Day Pay<sup>SM</sup> and learn how to get help with expenses health insurance doesn\'t cover, get to know us at aflac.com.</p> \n<p>Aflac herein means American Family Life Assurance Company of <span class="xn-location">Columbus</span> and American Family Life Assurance Company of <span class="xn-location">New York</span>. Claims are generally met by insurance companies or state-run workers compensation fund.<br><br>Let us take a look at the industrys three major themes:</br></br></br></br></p>\n<ul>\n <li style="text-align:justify;">The demand for workers compensation insurance has been boosted by increase in employment in the manufacturing and construction sectors that have been gaining momentum. According to the Bureau of Labor Statistics, job opportunities in both these industries have risen at a rapid rate. Increased exposure to these sectors leads to higher premiums for industry players.<br>&nbsp;</br></li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n <li style="text-align:justify;">Pricing pressure might weigh on premiums. Though other business lines in the insurance industry will continue to witness improved pricing, workers compensation is likely to witness a decline in rates. Miller</span>, executive vice president; chief operating officer, Aflac U.S.; president, Aflac Group. In this newly created role, Monroy will be responsible for overseeing Aflac\'s U.S. innovation delivery system and driving transformational market opportunities to diversify Aflac\'s enterprise business portfolio. </p> \n<p>Monroy brings to Aflac more than 25 years of well-rounded experience that includes business segment leadership responsibility, strategic planning, business development, marketing and sales, operations and finance. Before joining Aflac, he served most recently as chief marketing officer for CNO Financial Group, having held leadership positions of increasing responsibility at CNO and its subsidiaries, including president of Colonial Penn Life Insurance Company and various leadership roles at Bankers Life &amp; Casualty Company. His early career began with management roles at Procter &amp; Gamble in <span class="xn-location">Mexico</span> and later with Carrier Corporation/United Technologies in the U.S. and abroad.</p> \n<p>Monroy earned a bachelor\'s degree in public accounting from Universidad Iberoamericana and a Master of Business Administration from <span class="xn-org">Harvard University</span>. </p> \n<p>Commenting on the announcement, <span class="xn-person">Virgil Miller</span> said: "With our ongoing emphasis on innovation and transformation, I am pleased Gerardo is joining the Aflac team in this newly created role. Given his extensive track record of delivering strong results and his proven acumen in strategy, profit and loss management, marketing and operations, Gerardo\'s leadership will be an enormous asset to Aflac. We look forward to his focus on powering innovation to sustain our market leadership as we navigate and develop new markets, while targeting our customers\' new and continually evolving needs."</p> \n<p><b><u>About Aflac Incorporated<br /></u></b>Aflac Incorporated (<a href="/q?s=afl">AFL</a>) is a Fortune 500 company, helping provide protection to more than 50 million people through its subsidiaries in <span class="xn-location">Japan</span> and the U.S., where it is a leading supplemental insurer by paying cash fast when policyholders get sick or injured. A dividend is the distribution of a company\'s earnings paid out to shareholders; it\'s often viewed by its dividend yield, a metric that measures a dividend as a percent of the current stock price. Many academic studies show that dividends make up large portions of long-term returns, and in many cases, dividend contributions surpass one-third of total returns.</p>\n<p><b>Aflac in Focus</b></p>\n<p>Aflac (AFL) is headquartered in Columbus, and is in the Finance sector. This compares to the Insurance - Accident and Health industry\'s yield of 1.1% and the S&amp;P 500\'s yield of 1.98%.</p>\n<p>Taking a look at the company\'s dividend growth, its current annualized dividend of $1.08 is up 3.8% from last year. In the past five-year period, Aflac has increased its dividend 5 times on a year-over-year basis for an average annual increase of 8.49%. Future dividend growth will depend on earnings growth as well as payout ratio, which is the proportion of a company\'s annual earnings per share that it pays out as a dividend. Aflac\'s current payout ratio is 25%. This means it paid out 25% of its trailing 12-month EPS as dividend.</p>\n<p>Earnings growth looks solid for AFL for this fiscal year. Today\'s first-ever delivery to Roswell Park Comprehensive Cancer Center follows more than 18 months of child-centered research conducted with children, parents and medical providers at the Aflac Cancer and Blood Disorders Center of Children\'s Healthcare of <span class="xn-location">Atlanta</span>. </p> \n<div class="PRN_ImbeddedAssetReference" id="DivAssetPlaceHolder3570">\n <p><img src="https://s.yimg.com/uu/api/res/1.2/NbtP4t86SnY.SMJrFjqRZw--/YXBwaWQ9eXRhY2h5b247cT03NTs-/http://globalfinance.zenfs.com/en_us/Finance/US_AFTP_PRNEWSWIRE_LIVE/My_Special_Aflac_Duck_Flocks-9c9565c625564bf93eca10d0d8b0b9dd" class="editorial" title="Alex, a child with cancer, receives a My Special Aflac Duck at Roswell Park Comprehensive Cancer Center on Aug. 23, 2019." alt="Alex, a child with cancer, receives a My Special Aflac Duck at Roswell Park Comprehensive Cancer Center on Aug. 23, 2019." /></p> \n</div>\n<p>"We\'re focused on bringing <i>My Special Aflac Duck</i> to more and more children across the country. "Delivering&nbsp;<i>My Special Aflac Duck</i>&nbsp;to each child with cancer has been our mission since this program started last year, and we are grateful to Roswell Park Comprehensive Cancer Center for bringing us one step closer to reaching that goal."</p> \n<p>At today\'s delivery event, attendees were treated to a demonstration<i>, </i>highlighting how <i>My Special Aflac Duck</i> can help bring comfort and joy to children as they go through their cancer care. After the demonstration, children and their parents went on a fun scavenger hunt, finding clues and visiting various locations at the hospital, eventually leading them to the discovery of their very own <i>My Special Aflac Duck</i>. </p> \n<p>"We are thrilled to introduce <i>My Special Aflac Duck</i> to the children receiving cancer treatment at Roswell Park Comprehensive Cancer Center," The Aflac Foundation, Inc. President <span class="xn-person">Kathelen Amos</span> said. "The Aflac Duck has become a tangible, innovative companion for children as they go through their cancer journey. We are making an impact on such an important cause and couldn\'t be more proud."</p> \n<p>"<i>My Special Aflac Duck</i> can help our youngest patients to get through some of their toughest days," President and CEO of Roswell Park Comprehensive Cancer Center Dr. <span class="xn-person">Candace Johnson</span> said. "These cuddly companions bring comfort and connection while helping kids understand their treatments a little better, and I want to thank everyone at Aflac for their generosity and thoughtfulness in giving kids at Roswell Park and the Courage of Carly Fund a fuzzy friend to hug as they go through treatments."</p> \n<p>Congressman <span class="xn-person">Brian Higgins</span>, Co-Chair of the House of Representatives Cancer Caucus, said, "We are pleased to join in welcoming the <i>My Special Aflac Duck</i> to Roswell Park Comprehensive Cancer Center.&nbsp; This exciting robotic duck helps provide comfort and creative communication opportunities that can help children at Roswell Park and across the country cope with cancer."</p> \n<p>To date, Aflac has hosted special delivery events for <i>My Special Aflac Duck</i> in seven markets (<span class="xn-location">Atlanta</span>; <span class="xn-location">Houston</span>; <span class="xn-location">Nashville</span>; <span class="xn-location">New Orleans</span>; <span class="xn-location">Omaha</span>; <span class="xn-location">Columbia, South Carolina</span>; and <span class="xn-location">Orange County, California</span>) and has distributed ducks to children in 47 states. Aflac will continue to expand its <i>My Special Aflac Duck</i> campaign to hospitals across the country, providing a <i>My Special Aflac Duck</i> to any child diagnosed with cancer in <span class="xn-location">the United States</span>, ages three and above, for free through participating hospitals. To date, Aflac has invested more than&nbsp;$3 million&nbsp;for the research, design and delivery of&nbsp;<i>My Special Aflac Duck</i>&nbsp;across the nation. Health care professionals interested in obtaining <i>My Special Aflac Ducks</i> for pediatric cancer patients should go to AflacChildhoodCancer.org to complete the simple registration process and begin placing orders.</p> \n<p>In addition to <i>My Special Aflac Duck</i>, Sproutel has created a companion app available on the Apple App Store and Google Play. The app can be downloaded on smartphones and tablets free of charge. Additional features of <i>My Special Aflac Duck</i> include:</p> \n<ul type="disc">\n <li><b>Emotional expression</b>: Seven RFID-enabled feeling cards help children communicate; the duck acts out a given feeling when that feeling card is tapped to its chest. </li>\n <li><b>Medical and nurturing play</b>: A chemotherapy port allows children to mirror their care experiences via play, giving them a sense of control during the process. The duck\'s no-cost companion app allows users to "bathe" it, "feed" it and give it "medicine" via augmented reality. </li>\n <li><b>Music, singing and nuzzling</b>: The duck sings when music is played. Customizable sounds include gentle waves, wind and a farm. </li>\n <li><b>Breathing and heartbeat</b>: The duck produces a naturalistic heartbeat and deep breathing, which caregivers can incorporate into calming routines and exercises. </li>\n <li><b>Batteries and accessories: </b>Provided so it is ready to use out of the box. </li>\n <li><b>Convenience</b>: A removable skin, which can be washed to adhere to hospital hygiene standards.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>"It\'s an honor to be a part of something so special and impactful," <span class="xn-person">Aflac</span> Senior Vice President, Chief ESG and Communications Officer <span class="xn-person">Catherine Hernandez-Blades</span> said. "For more than two decades, Aflac has been dedicating time and resources to helping children and families cope with childhood cancer. <i>My Special Aflac Duck</i> can help provide countless hours of support and comfort to the children at Roswell Park Comprehensive Cancer Center, and we are grateful to our partners there for helping us advance our mission."</p> \n<p>Since 1995, Aflac has contributed more than <span class="xn-money">$136 million</span> to the pediatric cancer cause, including more than <span class="xn-money">$500,000</span> donated each month by 17,000 independent agents licensed to sell Aflac products. The funds are committed directly from their monthly commission checks. With that in mind, this article will work through how we can use Return On Equity (ROE) to better understand a business. To keep the lesson grounded in practicality, we\'ll use ROE to better understand Aflac Incorporated (<a href="https://simplywall.st/stocks/us/insurance/nyse-afl/aflac?utm_medium=finance_user&amp;utm_source=yahoo&amp;utm_campaign=Intro_ticker&amp;blueprint=776992" target="_blank">NYSE:AFL</a>). </p> \n<p> Over the last twelve months <strong>Aflac has recorded a ROE of 11%</strong>. One way to conceptualize this, is that for each $1 of shareholders\' equity it has, the company made $0.11 in profit. </p> \n<p> <span class="veryHighlightLink"> <a href="https://simplywall.st/stocks/us/insurance/nyse-afl/aflac?utm_medium=finance_user&amp;utm_source=yahoo&amp;utm_campaign=CTA_ticker&amp;blueprint=776992"> See our latest analysis for Aflac </a> </span> </p> \n<h3> How Do You Calculate ROE? </h3> \n<p> The <strong>formula for return on equity</strong> is: </p> \n<p> Return on Equity = Net Profit  Shareholders\' Equity </p> \n<p> Or for Aflac: </p> \n<p> 11% = US$3.1b  US$28b (Based on the trailing twelve months to June 2019.) </p> \n<p> Most know that net profit is the total earnings after all expenses, but the concept of shareholders\' equity is a little more complicated. It is all earnings retained by the company, plus any capital paid in by shareholders. Shareholders\' equity can be calculated by subtracting the total liabilities of the company from the total assets of the company. </p> \n<h3> What Does ROE Mean? </h3> \n<p> Return on Equity measures a company\'s profitability against the profit it has kept for the business (plus any capital injections). The \'return\' is the amount earned after tax over the last twelve months. A higher profit will lead to a higher ROE. So, all else being equal, <strong>a high ROE is better than a low one</strong>. That means ROE can be used to compare two businesses. </p> \n<h3> Does Aflac Have A Good Return On Equity? </h3> \n<p> By comparing a company\'s ROE with its industry average, we can get a quick measure of how good it is. However, this method is only useful as a rough check, because companies do differ quite a bit within the same industry classification. Pleasingly, Aflac has a superior ROE than the average (8.6%) company in the Insurance industry. </p> \n<figure> \n <a href="https://simplywall.st/stocks/us/insurance/nyse-afl/aflac?utm_medium=finance_user&amp;utm_source=yahoo&amp;utm_campaign=Infographic&amp;blueprint=776992#last-perf" target="_blank"> <img src="https://s.yimg.com/uu/api/res/1.2/55NQEFanyxVLk9yTCexXBA--/YXBwaWQ9eXRhY2h5b247cT03NTs-/https://media.zenfs.com/en/simply_wall_st__316/09651689b9763245d5df1cb4e2fd53d8" alt="NYSE:AFL Past Revenue and Net Income, August 22nd 2019"> </img></a> \n <figcaption>\n  NYSE:AFL Past Revenue and Net Income, August 22nd 2019\n </figcaption> \n</figure> \n<p> That\'s clearly a positive. We think a high ROE, alone, is usually enough to justify further research into a company. For example, <strong><a href="https://simplywall.st/stocks/us/insurance/nyse-afl/aflac?utm_medium=finance_user&amp;utm_source=yahoo&amp;blueprint=776992#insider_trading" target="_blank">I often check if insiders have been buying shares </a></strong>. </p>\n<h3> Why You Should Consider Debt When Looking At ROE </h3> \n<p> Most companies need money -- from somewhere -- to grow their profits. That cash can come from retained earnings, issuing new shares (equity), or debt. In the first two cases, the ROE will capture this use of capital to grow. In the latter case, the use of debt will improve the returns, but will not change the equity. In this manner the use of debt will boost ROE, even though the core economics of the business stay the same. </p> \n<h3> Combining Aflac\'s Debt And Its 11% Return On Equity </h3> \n<p> While Aflac does have some debt, with debt to equity of just 0.27, we wouldn\'t say debt is excessive. The combination of modest debt and a very respectable ROE suggests this is a business worth watching. Judicious use of debt to improve returns can certainly be a good thing, although it does elevate risk slightly and reduce future optionality. </p> \n<h3> The Bottom Line On ROE </h3> \n<p> Return on equity is useful for comparing the quality of different businesses. Companies that can achieve high returns on equity without too much debt are generally of good quality. If two companies have around the same level of debt to equity, and one has a higher ROE, I\'d generally prefer the one with higher ROE. </p> \n<p> But when a business is high quality, the market often bids it up to a price that reflects this. The rate at which profits are likely to grow, relative to the expectations of profit growth reflected in the current price, must be considered, too. This prompted them to shift to riskier assets such as equity, moving away from safe haven assets like treasuries. This consequently led to a decline in bond, leading to a rise in bond yields that supported gains in the U.S. dollar.</p>\n<p style="text-align:justify;">The U.S. dollar has held on to the kings throne despite rate cuts, yield curve inversion and recessionary fears in the economy.</p>\n<p style="text-align:justify;">Slowdown fears in several economies of the world have led their central banks to slash interest rates to aid growth. Central banks in New Zealand, South Korea, Indonesia, South Africa, Turkey, Peru, India and the Philippines have had one or more rate cuts in recent times to keep slowdown at bay. Weakness in these economies have also put pressure on their currencies.</p>\n<p style="text-align:justify;">The greenback, however, remains strong as the U.S. economy is relatively better positioned compared with other economies, thus gaining favor from investors, who still view it as a safer currency.</p>\n<p style="text-align:justify;">However, President Trump has held a strong dollar for hitting exports and calling upon the Fed for interest rate cuts to help business growth.</p>\n<p style="text-align:justify;">In a twitter post, President Trump complained about a strong dollar, which "is sadly hurting other parts of the world."</p>\n<p style="text-align:justify;"><strong>Stimulus Measures</strong></p>\n<p style="text-align:justify;">Stimulus hopes from U.S., China and Germany put aside the fears of a global economic meltdown, which led investors to move to riskier assets.<br>The White House is considering a temporary payroll tax cut, in order to put more cash in the hands of consumers to spend more and drive demand, thereby stimulating the economy.</br></p>\n<p style="text-align:justify;">China in an effort to spur its economic growth has changed the way commercial lenders set interest rates for loans to reduce borrowing costs. Chinas economy has been languishing from trade war with the United States and is in dire need for stimulus.</p>\n<p style="text-align:justify;">On the other hand, Germany is readying stimulus plans, which would be put into effect if Europes largest economy moves into recession. According to the 2019 Insurance Market Report from <a href="https://www.globenewswire.com/Tracker?data=4h3XVxDfWOpvXsPfG6_2WeiA7d8sE5A918J1QTrFgRIBHrkH5ml21BAt6fxw3_nkWJFwQjPMOMNG3spbgH_70g==" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">Aon</a>, a leading global professional services firm providing a broad range of risk, retirement and health solutions, the catastrophe losses made 2017 and 2018 the most expensive two-year period for insurers ever recorded. The overall market remains resilient, but industry players need to adjust to a rapidly hardening market.<br /></p> \n<p><strong>Quotes</strong><br>Insurers capital positions remain strong for primary and reinsurance markets. The Canadian insurance market in particular continues to attract capital because of its relative profitability and stable political environment, said Russell Quilley, Chief Broking Officer, Aon in Canada.</br></p> \n<p>Its clear, however, that we are in the midst of a transitioning market, and brokers, carriers and clients will need to think differently from the way they have in over a decade, added Quilley. In a volatile business environment, its imperative for industry players to not only understand the impact of weather-related events and other changes, but also leverage the tools and expertise available to them. Putting innovation to work, and finding efficiencies in risk management and transfer solutions, will be more critical than ever.</p> \n<p><strong>Key findings</strong></p> \n<ul type="disc">\n <li>At US$225 billion, inflation-adjusted economic losses in 2018 were the second highest on record and followed losses of US$358 billion in 2017. Cyclones and hurricanes were the most significant cause (20% of total economic losses), along with wildfires in California, flooding in Japan and drought in the United States. Insured losses reached US$90 billion, down from US$134 billion in 2017.</li>\n <li>Against those losses, global insurers had a larger capital base, which grew 3.3%, to US$4.4 trillion, by the end of 2017.</li>\n <li>Canada continues to be an attractive location for capital deployment; the Canadian industrys cumulative net combined ratio of 98.3% compares favorably with the U.S. (98.6%) and UK (99.7%) markets.</li>\n <li>The reinsurance market is well capitalized, despite a 3% decline in total reinsurance capital from 2017 to 2018. Global reinsurer capital stood at an estimated US$585 billion in 2018, still 30% higher than in 2011.</li>\n <li>The loss events of 2017/18 had the biggest impact on the alternative capital market, which includes catastrophe bonds and industry loss warranties. Growth has slowed as the entry of new funds is being offset by redemption and losses from catastrophic events.</li>\n <li>The top risks for insurers identified in the 2019 Aon Insurance Market Report include cyber attacks and data breaches, damage to reputation/brand, business interruption, regulatory changes, weather/natural disasters and an economic slowdown.</li>\n</ul> \n<p>Click here, to read the full <a href="https://www.globenewswire.com/Tracker?data=dyTJyaTUKIO8h3K52O1LqZZttU-ENoV_cI37zqHMO4tVhbnSpqmqHEYPNiGpRv93sgm98fDz6EGczSByb5HajfyOVKiNS1eo421R0CSMAW5NyUdMbJ2pQjmXLLuMljZMh-oo0437DgiH56TArc0Uig==" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">report</a>.</p> \n<p><strong><em>About Aon<br> </br></em></strong>Aon plc (<a href="/q?s=aon">AON</a>) is a leading global professional services firm providing a broad range of risk, retirement and health solutions. Our 50,000 colleagues in 120 countries empower results for clients by using proprietary data and analytics to deliver insights that reduce volatility and improve performance.</p> \n<p>Follow Aon on Twitter: <a href="https://www.globenewswire.com/Tracker?data=iPIK6j3CYRnRi0fHGJJFXdNqcCQkH0J5sDKmRnrTsZDE7tpU0N9QX_mFgIuUtmvPMZXs0B83N5gYrW9QlJxYd0Bh53v5KIJQ2nFkpm2qtiA=" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">https://twitter.com/Aon_plc</a><br> Sign up for News Alerts: <a href="https://www.globenewswire.com/Tracker?data=6YpCRZepBpMlDAQM3sFOM-zCOLYZvPN_13PLslj31snFc4vjnyTyF0SMElSSV7VftTDBTzJjfUrTJ4jrVlgXpD6qVfwplP5DTL0r-RXxfEyr5tRwLzdj9WIwGaNw8dInzrIWqlxePH-RZglRyvRpng==" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">http://aon.mediaroom.com/index.php?s=58</a></br></p> \n<p><strong>Media Contacts</strong><br>For further information please contact&nbsp;<a href="https://www.globenewswire.com/Tracker?data=x3tt4QSp9YUHVga-SyaEO69i2G0J2wgzYCWGrYoSzXfvxtLpEn2qspb4Q97m4xpoyuQQ-jFZ_zvwiOQy0k1DoZQVMEmQGYisAotkdIpvvns=" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">Alexandre Daudelin</a> (514.982.4910)</br></p> \n<p></p> \n<img src="https://s1.yimg.com/uu/api/res/1.2/mSR.mQxCxrqdYkf6vtPovw--/YXBwaWQ9eXRhY2h5b247cT03NTs-/http://globalfinance.zenfs.com/en_us/Finance/US_AFTP_GlobeNewsWire_EmailNotif_LIVE/ti?nf=NzcwMDAwNiMzMDkxNTk0IzIwODQ5MTY=" class="editorial" width="1" height="1">\n<style type="text/css">.gnwlistitemmarginbottom {margin-bottom: 10.0px !important;} \n.gnwtablebottommargin {margin-bottom: 10.0px !important;} \n.gnwcellpaddingleft0 {padding-left: 0.0px !important;} \n.gnwverticalaligntop {vertical-align: top !important;} \n.gnwtextaligncenter {text-align: center !important;} \n.gnwcellparagraphmargin {margin-bottom: 0px !important; During each week of the regular season, players were challenged to look at the Aon Risk Reward holes in a new way, using their previous experience to develop insights and take calculated risks that would allow them to outperform their competitors. </p> \n<p>"I\'m really proud of the work we did this year and am gratified to win an award that recognizes a consistently high-level of performance over the entire season, particularly on some of the toughest holes in the game," said Koepka. The scoring system, identical on both the PGA TOUR and LPGA, is intuitive and produces a compelling risk/reward narrative throughout the season. The Aon Risk Reward Challenge takes the best two scores from every participating event a player competes in, ensuring that all play is counted and providing a small advantage to those that make the cut with the winner having the best average score to par across the season. Players must compete in a minimum of 40 rounds throughout the season.</p> \n<p>The Challenge runs across regular season tournaments (36 PGA TOUR; 29 LPGA), with CBS Sports and Golf Channel as official broadcast partners. Gallagher&nbsp;&amp; Co. today announced the acquisition of the University Services business of <span class="xn-location">Mission Viejo, California</span>-based benefits broker and consultant Garnett-Powers &amp; Associates Insurance Services, Inc. Terms of the transaction were not disclosed.</p> \n<div class="PRN_ImbeddedAssetReference" id="DivAssetPlaceHolder1"> \n <p><img src="https://s.yimg.com/uu/api/res/1.2/OjInVJC6Yzeno0S5Q__ltw--/YXBwaWQ9eXRhY2h5b247cT03NTs-/http://globalfinance.zenfs.com/en_us/Finance/US_AFTP_PRNEWSWIRE_LIVE/Arthur_J_Gallagher__Co-56a82f35140a572abfd8e2789ff95ebf" class="editorial" title="Arthur J. Gallagher &amp; Co.)" /></p> \n</div> \n<p>Established in 1996, Garnett-Powers &amp; Associates\' University Services business offers medical, dental, vision, life, AD&amp;D and disability insurance plans to university postdoctoral scholars and visiting scholars. They also offer health insurance plans to university students. Their proprietary software automates the process, providing a customized enrollment suite, benefits administration and file transfer services for clients and plan participants. <span class="xn-person">Steve Johnson</span> and his associates will continue to operate from their current location under the direction of <span class="xn-person">Norbert Chung</span>, head of Gallagher\'s Western region employee benefit consulting and brokerage operations.</p> \n<p>"Garnett-Powers &amp; Associates\' University Services business adds a unique and vital link to our already strong Higher Education practice, while also bringing a unique platform to customize the enrollment process," said J. <span class="xn-person">Patrick Gallagher, Jr.</span>, Chairman, President and CEO.   'content': '<p></p>\n<p><b>Gallagher\'s 2019/2020 Salary Planning Survey Reveals Organizations Are Using Spot Bonuses, Performance-Based Compensation and Incentive Programs to Limit Structural Salary Increases, With Many Citing Higher Health Insurance Costs as a Primary Factor</b></p> \n<p><span class="xn-location">ROLLING MEADOWS, Ill.</span>, <span class="xn-chron">Aug. 6, 2019</span> /PRNewswire/ --&nbsp;While economists and policymakers often argue that sustained low unemployment incentivizes employers to raise salaries, many organizations are experimenting with new ways to prevent base salary costs from rising by more than 3 percent annually according to Gallagher\'s 2019/2020<i> Salary Planning Survey Report</i>.&nbsp;Employers of all sizes and across all industries are using variable compensation models and customized benefit options to attract and retain workers for whom the highest possible pay may not necessarily be the top factor in deciding where to work.</p> \n<div class="PRN_ImbeddedAssetReference" id="DivAssetPlaceHolder1"> \n <p><img src="https://s.yimg.com/uu/api/res/1.2/wr2N633AF_awDF4zz3LSyQ--/YXBwaWQ9eXRhY2h5b247cT03NTs-/http://globalfinance.zenfs.com/en_us/Finance/US_AFTP_PRNEWSWIRE_LIVE/US_Employers_Shifting_Toward_Variable-ead317c86b900676da39ec907ddd4d28" class="editorial" title="Gallagher Logo (PRNewsfoto/Gallagher)" alt="Gallagher Logo (PRNewsfoto/Gallagher)" /></p> \n</div> \n<p>The 2019/2020<i> Salary Planning Survey Report </i>found nearly four out of 10 (39 percent) organizations now use variable pay for at least one employee group. While the tight labor market is directly responsible for the rise in employee referral, hiring and retention bonuses, 20 percent of employers reported using lump sum awards for at least one employee group. And approximately one-third (32-35 percent) rely on variable pay for executive and manager-level employees, while nearly a quarter (22-25 percent) of employers also offer variable pay to lower-level employees, including those already qualifying for overtime pay under the Fair Labor Standards Act. The portion of compensation subject to performance rises from 5 percent for low-level workers to 25 percent for executives. </p> \n<p>Additionally, more than one out of four (26 percent) employers indicated higher healthcare costs were a primary factor for keeping salary increases in check. This aligns with Gallagher\'s 2019<i> Benefits Strategy &amp; Benchmarking Survey</i>, where nearly half (47 percent) of employers noted that controlling employee benefit costs was a top human resource priority. That said, employers that implement healthcare cost-sharing tactics, such as increasing employee premium contributions, must be conscious of the fact that employees and their families  just like their employers  suffer the financial pressure of higher healthcare expenses. As a result, lower salary increases coupled with higher healthcare expenses can have a negative impact on employee retention.</p> \n<p>"Through our in-depth analysis of the data, as well as countless conversations with employers, decision makers appear reluctant to raise salaries across the board because this significantly increases operating costs both in the near and long-term," said <span class="xn-person">William F. Ziebell</span>, CEO of Gallagher Employee Benefits Consulting and Brokerage. "It\'s important to understand that pay increases are not the only solution for attracting and retaining employees  particularly Millennials. By leveraging tailor-made benefits and compensation strategies, organizations can create a deeper connection with their workforce and, at the same time, keep expenses in check. A few examples include flex-time or remote-working options, as well as health and wellness programs."</p> \n<p><b>ABOUT THE 2019/2020 SALARY PLANNING SURVEY REPORT <br /></b>The 2019/2020<i> Salary Planning Survey Report </i>from Gallagher helps employers make fully informed decisions about compensation and benefit plans and programs that attract and retain top talent without breaking the bank. During April and <span class="xn-chron">May 2019</span>, the survey captured data from company leaders, human-resource and financial practitioners representing 943 organizations, with 53 percent of respondents working for for-profit organizations and 47 percent for non-profits. View the report here: ajg.com/US-SPS-2019</p> \n<p><b>ABOUT GALLAGHER<br /></b><span class="xn-person">Arthur J. Gallagher</span> &amp; Co. (NYSE:&nbsp;AJG), a global insurance brokerage, risk management and consulting services firm, is headquartered in&nbsp;Rolling Meadows, <span class="xn-location">Illinois</span>. The company has operations in 35 countries and offers client service capabilities in more than 150 countries around the world through a network of correspondent brokers and consultants.</p> \n<p>Contact:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <br><span class="xn-person">Mary Schwartz</span>, Gallagher<br>847.378.5893<br><a target="_blank" href="mailto:mary_schwartz@ajg.com" rel="nofollow">mary_schwartz@ajg.com</a> </br></br></br></p> \n<p>&nbsp;</p> \n<p id="PURL"><img src="https://c212.net/c/img/favicon.png?sn=CG28147&amp;sd=2019-08-06" class="editorial" title="Cision ID" width="12" height="12" alt="Cision"> View original content to download multimedia:<a id="PRNURL" rel="nofollow" href="http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/us-employers-shifting-toward-variable-compensation-and-customized-benefits-to-hold-annual-salary-increases-below-3-percent-300893905.html">http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/us-employers-shifting-toward-variable-compensation-and-customized-benefits-to-hold-annual-salary-increases-below-3-percent-300893905.html</a></img></p>\n<p></p> \n<style type="text/css">span.prnews_span{font-size:8pt !important;font-family:"Arial" !important;color:black !important;} \na.prnews_a{color:blue !important;} \nli.prnews_li{font-size:8pt !important;font-family:"Arial" !important;color:black !important;} \np.prnews_p{font-size:0.62em !important;font-family:"Arial" !important;color:black !important;margin:0in !important;} \n;} \n</style>',

The new products feature innovative benefits for diabetes, cancer and telemedicine services, demonstrating Chubb\'s continuing commitment to crafting employee benefits that can help today\'s employers strengthen the financial security of their workforce and help employees manage their healthcare costs.</p> \n<p>"Our approach to product development addresses leading concerns in today\'s healthcare arena, such as diabetes and cancer," said <span class="xn-person">Janet Buzil</span>, Vice President of Product Development and Marketing. "With more than 30 million Americans living with diabetes<sup>1</sup>, primarily Type 2, and one in eight women developing breast cancer<sup>2</sup>, the time is now to build innovative products that promote healthier lifestyles and provide Americans with better financial protection." </p> \n<p>Key critical illness benefits:</p> \n<ul type="disc">\n <li>Diabetes benefit that promotes healthy behavior by paying benefits while the insured is enrolled in nutritional counseling, gym membership or other programs, after being diagnosed with diabetes.</li>\n</ul>\n<ul type="disc">\n <li>Cancer enhancement package that pays the full face amount for all cancers of the breast, even when diagnosed as carcinoma in situ (non-invasive cancer).</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Key accident benefits:</p> \n<ul type="disc">\n <li>Telemedicine services benefit aimed at meeting the changing ways employees receive care. </li>\n</ul>\n<ul type="disc">\n <li>Post-traumatic stress disorder benefit. </li>\n</ul>\n<ul type="disc">\n <li>Occupational benefit offered with critical illness plans is now available with accident to cover Hepatitis B, C, or D; HIV; MRSA infection; rabies; tetanus; and tuberculosis contracted at work. </li>\n</ul>\n<p>Quoting for these products, which include the flexibility for employers to customize plans that meet the needs of their employees, will begin this month for effective dates of <span class="xn-chron">Jan. 1, 2020</span>. </p> \n<p>"We are proud to share these new enhancements in response to our partners\' needs and look forward to seeing how they are received by industry-leading benefits brokers and their clients," said <span class="xn-person">Jon Wayland</span>, Senior Vice President, Sales, Chubb Workplace Benefits. "The key to meeting the benefit needs of today\'s employers is flexibility and customization  in product choices, plan designs, enrollment support and billing."</p> \n<p>Chubb Workplace Benefits was recently recognized by Eastbridge Consulting as a Voluntary Benefits Sales Growth Leader for 2018. It marks the fourth time in five years Chubb has won in their category  achieving this award in 2014, 2015 and 2016. </p> \n<p><b>About Chubb <br /></b>Chubb is the world\'s largest publicly traded property and casualty insurance company. With operations in 54 countries and territories, Chubb provides commercial and personal property and casualty insurance, personal accident and supplemental health insurance, reinsurance and life insurance to a diverse group of clients. The company is also defined by its extensive product and service offerings, broad distribution capabilities, exceptional financial strength and local operations globally. Parent company Chubb Limited is listed on the New York Stock Exchange (<a href="/q?s=cb">CB</a>) and is a component of the S&amp;P 500 index. We\'ll look at Chubb Limited\'s (<a href="https://simplywall.st/stocks/us/insurance/nyse-cb/chubb?utm_medium=finance_user&amp;utm_source=yahoo&amp;utm_campaign=Intro_ticker&amp;blueprint=795822" target="_blank">NYSE:CB</a>) P/E ratio and reflect on what it tells us about the company\'s share price. <strong>Chubb has a price to earnings ratio of 19.03</strong>, based on the last twelve months. In other words, at today\'s prices, investors are paying $19.03 for every $1 in prior year profit. </p> \n<p> <span class="veryHighlightLink"> <a href="https://simplywall.st/stocks/us/insurance/nyse-cb/chubb?utm_medium=finance_user&amp;utm_source=yahoo&amp;utm_campaign=CTA_ticker&amp;blueprint=795822"> Check out our latest analysis for Chubb </a> </span> </p> \n<h3> How Do I Calculate Chubb\'s Price To Earnings Ratio? </h3> \n<p> The <strong>formula for price to earnings </strong> is: </p> \n<p> Price to Earnings Ratio = Price per Share  Earnings per Share (EPS) </p> \n<p> Or for Chubb: </p> \n<p> P/E of 19.03 = $156.28  $8.21 (Based on the year to June 2019.) </p> \n<h3> Is A High P/E Ratio Good? </h3> \n<p> A higher P/E ratio means that investors are paying <strong>a higher price</strong> for each $1 of company earnings. All else being equal, it\'s better to pay a low price -- but as Warren Buffett said, \'It\'s far better to buy a wonderful company at a fair price than a fair company at a wonderful price.\' </p> \n<h3> Does Chubb Have A Relatively High Or Low P/E For Its Industry? </h3> \n<p> One good way to get a quick read on what market participants expect of a company is to look at its P/E ratio. As you can see below, Chubb has a higher P/E than the average company (15.7) in the insurance industry. </p> \n<figure> \n <a href="https://simplywall.st/stocks/us/insurance/nyse-cb/chubb?utm_medium=finance_user&amp;utm_source=yahoo&amp;utm_campaign=Infographic&amp;blueprint=795822#PE-PEG-gauge" target="_blank"> <img src="https://s.yimg.com/uu/api/res/1.2/w7ZmFrSKPY7bHe2xFV_yvw--/YXBwaWQ9eXRhY2h5b247cT03NTs-/https://media.zenfs.com/en/simply_wall_st__316/1c98a80db40b6ba2f5af9369d7c339ad" alt="NYSE:CB Price Estimation Relative to Market, September 3rd 2019"> </img></a> \n <figcaption>\n  NYSE:CB Price Estimation Relative to Market, September 3rd 2019\n </figcaption> \n</figure> \n<p> That means that the market expects Chubb will outperform other companies in its industry. The market is optimistic about the future, but that doesn\'t guarantee future growth. So investors should always consider the P/E ratio alongside other factors, such as <strong><a href="https://simplywall.st/stocks/us/insurance/nyse-cb/chubb?utm_medium=finance_user&amp;utm_source=yahoo&amp;blueprint=795822#insider_trading" target="_blank">whether company directors have been buying shares</a></strong>. </p>\n<h3>How Growth Rates Impact P/E Ratios</h3> \n<p> P/E ratios primarily reflect market expectations around earnings growth rates. Earnings growth means that in the future the \'E\' will be higher. That means unless the share price increases, the P/E will reduce in a few years. A lower P/E should indicate the stock is cheap relative to others -- and that may attract buyers. </p> \n<p> Chubb had pretty flat EPS growth in the last year. But over the longer term (3 years), earnings per share have increased by 11%. And it has shrunk its earnings per share by 4.0% per year over the last five years. So you wouldn\'t expect a very high P/E. </p>\n<h3> Don\'t Forget: The P/E Does Not Account For Debt or Bank Deposits </h3> \n<p> It\'s important to note that the P/E ratio considers the market capitalization, not the enterprise value. Thus, the metric does not reflect cash or debt held by the company. Theoretically, a business can improve its earnings (and produce a lower P/E in the future) by investing in growth. That means taking on debt (or spending its cash). </p> \n<p> Such expenditure might be good or bad, in the long term, but the point here is that the balance sheet is not reflected by this ratio. </p> \n<h3> Is Debt Impacting Chubb\'s P/E? </h3> \n<p> Net debt totals 17% of Chubb\'s market cap. This could bring some additional risk, and reduce the number of investment options for management; worth remembering if you compare its P/E to businesses without debt. </p> \n<h3> The Verdict On Chubb\'s P/E Ratio </h3> \n<p> Chubb\'s P/E is 19 which is above average (17.3) in its market. With modest debt but no EPS growth in the last year, it\'s fair to say the P/E implies some optimism about future earnings, from the market. </p> \n<p> When the market is wrong about a stock, it gives savvy investors an opportunity. As value investor Benjamin Graham famously said, \'In the short run, the market is a voting machine but in the long run, it is a weighing machine.\' So this <strong>free</strong> <a href="https://simplywall.st/stocks/us/insurance/nyse-cb/chubb?utm_medium=finance_user&amp;utm_source=yahoo&amp;utm_campaign=Conc_ticker&amp;blueprint=795822#future">visualization of the analyst consensus on future earnings</a> could help you make the <strong>right decision</strong> about whether to buy, sell, or hold. </p> \n<p> Of course, <strong>you might find a fantastic investment by looking at a few good candidates.</strong> So take a peek at this <strong>free</strong> <a href="https://simplywall.st/user/views/16455/strong-past-earnings-growth-p-e-ratio-below-20?utm_medium=finance_user&amp;utm_source=yahoo&amp;utm_campaign=Conc_grid&amp;blueprint=795822" target="_blank">list of companies with modest (or no) debt, trading on a P/E below 20. </a> </p> \n<p> <i style="font-style:italic;">We aim to bring you long-term focused research analysis driven by fundamental data.   'content': '<p></p>\n<p><i>Report spotlights Biometric Privacy Act, iEncrpyt and cyber risks facing financial institutions</i></p> \n<p> WHITEHOUSE STATION, N.J. , Aug. 27, 2019 /CNW/ --&nbsp;Chubb\'s latest Cyber <a target="_blank" href="https://c212.net/c/link/?t=0&amp;l=en&amp;o=2562013-1&amp;h=867093285&amp;u=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.chubb.com%2Fus-en%2F_assets%2Fdoc%2Fcyber-infocus_july2019_updated.pdf&amp;a=InFocus+Report%2C" rel="nofollow">InFocus Report,</a> "Know the Latest Trends in Cyber Risks," outlines the newest cyber exposures that all institutions should have on their radar.</p> \n<div class="PRN_ImbeddedAssetReference" id="DivAssetPlaceHolder1"> \n <p><img src="https://s.yimg.com/uu/api/res/1.2/lEWYpO.eYUkr6dSt_9e6jA--/YXBwaWQ9eXRhY2h5b247cT03NTs-/http://globalfinance.zenfs.com/en_us/Finance/US_AFTP_CNWGROUP_CCM_LIVE/321965LOGO_Logo_Logo.jpg" class="editorial" title="" alt="" /></p> \n</div> \n<p>The first of these new risks surrounds a recent surge in Biometrics Information Privacy Act (BIPA) lawsuits, which has created a growing need for organizations to better understand current and emerging privacy laws. BIPA regulates the collection, use, storage, safeguarding, retention, and destruction of biometric identifierssuch as retina or iris scans and fingerprintsand biometric information that companies collect on their employees and customers. Biometric data regulation varies at the state level and has been a focus of U.S. federal and international legislators and regulators, so it is imperative that companies understand the legal requirements of each state and of the countries in which they conduct business.</p> \n<p>The second cyber risk comes from the emergence of a newly detected ransomware variantiEncrypt. It is characterized by mid-six to seven figure ransom demands and is spread through existing malware, such as Dridex or Emotet. With this growing threat in mind, malware detection and regular backups of main systems are increasingly important to protect against company data being held hostage. This type of event can cause severe business interruption.</p> \n<p>While cyber risks exist for all businesses, the vast amount of financial transactions and corresponding monetary opportunities for cyber criminals make financial institutions a prime target for bad actors. In fact, proprietary claims data from the <a target="_blank" href="https://c212.net/c/link/?t=0&amp;l=en&amp;o=2562013-1&amp;h=2228883031&amp;u=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.chubbcyberindex.com%2F&amp;a=Chubb+Cyber+Index" rel="nofollow">Chubb Cyber Index</a><sup>SM</sup>&nbsp;shows that the median cost of a cyber incident has doubled for financial institutions in the past three years.</p> \n<p>"Financial institutions were some of the early adopters of cyber security technology and training due to their central role in the economy and the need to protect their clients\' sensitive data," said Michael Tanenbaum , Head of Chubb Cyber North America . "However, we are seeing cyber criminals continually evolve in their methods of attacking the industrymeaning that the financial services space is still fertile ground for bad actors looking to exploit any gaps that they can find."</p> \n<p>Compounding this concern is that many of these attacks are preventable. Human error tops the list of cyber attacks hitting the industry, tied with hacking, accounting for 21% of cyber claims for Chubb\'s financial institution clients in 2019. Rounding out the top three sources of cyber attacks is phishing and other forms of social engineering at 18%.</p> \n<p>"In general, financial institutions are at the cutting edge in terms of cyber security software and processes," added Anthony Dolce , Vice President, Chubb Cyber Claims. "However, every day we see situations where one stray click on a well-targeted phishing email can result in losses of millions of dollars." </p> \n<p><b>About Chubb\'s Cyber InFocus Report</b></p> \n<p>Chubb\'s Cyber InFocus report, first launched in early 2018, provides insights into the effects of cyber risks and trends on specific industries or business segments each quarter. Such insight is based on Chubb\'s use of third-party research, as well as proprietary claims data from more than two decades of insuring organizations against evolving cyber threats. </p> \n<p>Visit <a target="_blank" href="https://c212.net/c/link/?t=0&amp;l=en&amp;o=2562013-1&amp;h=2140063270&amp;u=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.chubb.com%2Fcyber&amp;a=www.chubb.com%2Fcyber" rel="nofollow">www.chubb.com/cyber</a> to read this quarter\'s Chubb Cyber InFocus Report, gain access to additional insight into risk mitigation practices, as well as real-time proprietary cyber claims data through the Chubb Cyber Index. Visit <a target="_blank" href="https://c212.net/c/link/?t=0&amp;l=en&amp;o=2562013-1&amp;h=2638040857&amp;u=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.chubb.com%2Fus-en%2Fclaims%2Fcyber-infocus.aspx&amp;a=Chubb+Cyber+InFocus" rel="nofollow">Chubb Cyber InFocus</a> to view a video on this quarter\'s topic.</p> \n<p>For more information on Chubb\'s cyber products and services, contact your local <a target="_blank" href="https://c212.net/c/link/?t=0&amp;l=en&amp;o=2562013-1&amp;h=1150407446&amp;u=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.chubb.com%2Fus-en%2Ffind-agent-page.aspx%3Futm_source%3Dpr%26utm_medium%3Dpressrelease&amp;a=Chubb+agent+or+broker" rel="nofollow">Chubb agent or broker</a>. </p> \n<p><b>About Chubb Cyber : <br /></b>Chubb is a leader in insuring cyber risk. Combining industry-leading underwriting and expert third-party incident response services, Chubb offers policies that are tailored to the specific needs and risks of its clients to help ensure they are ready with the tools and expertise necessary should a cyber incident occur. Moving swiftly to connect clients with the proper parties to minimize data loss is only part of what Chubb delivers. Keeping an eye on the ever-evolving cyber security landscape, Chubb looks for ways to do more for its clients by offering cutting-edge products and holistic services to each and every client.</p> \n<p><b>About Chubb: <br /></b>Chubb is the world\'s largest publicly traded property and casualty insurance company. With operations in 54 countries and territories, Chubb provides commercial and personal property and casualty insurance, personal accident and supplemental health insurance, reinsurance and life insurance to a diverse group of clients.&nbsp;As an underwriting company, we assess, assume and manage risk with insight and discipline.&nbsp;We service and pay our claims fairly and promptly. The company is also defined by its extensive product and service offerings, broad distribution capabilities, exceptional financial strength and local operations globally.&nbsp;Parent company Chubb Limited is listed on the New York Stock Exchange (<a href="/q?s=cb">CB</a>) and is a component of the S&amp;P 500 index.&nbsp;Chubb maintains executive offices in&nbsp;Zurich,&nbsp;New York,&nbsp;London, Paris&nbsp;and other locations, and employs more than 30,000 people worldwide.   'content': '<p>It has been about a month since the last earnings report for Chubb (CB). Shares have added about 2.2% in that time frame, outperforming the S&amp;P 500.</p>\n<p>Will the recent positive trend continue leading up to its next earnings release, or is Chubb due for a pullback? Before we dive into how investors and analysts have reacted as of late, let\'s take a quick look at its most recent earnings report in order to get a better handle on the important catalysts. </p>\n<p><strong>Chubb\'s Earnings Beat Estimates in Q2, Decrease Y/Y</strong><br><br>Chubb reported second-quarter 2019 core operating income of $2.60 per share, which outpaced the Zacks Consensus Estimate by 0.8%. The upside was driven by higher premium revenues. However, the bottom line dipped 3% from the year-ago quarter.<br><br><strong>Quarter in Detail</strong><br><br>Net premiums written improved 4.2% year over year to about $7.7 billion in the quarter. Net premiums earned rose 3% year over year to $7.29 billion.<br><br>Net investment income was $859 million, up 3.7% from the comparable quarter last year.<br><br>Property and casualty underwriting income was $727 million, down 11.7% from the year-ago period.<br><br>Combined ratio expanded 170 basis points (bps) to 90.1%.<br><br>Chubb reported after-tax catastrophe loss of $221 million in the reported quarter, wider than the year-ago quarters loss of $173 million.<br><br><strong>Segment Update</strong><br><br><strong>North America Commercial P&amp;C Insurance</strong>: Net premiums written increased 6% year over year to about $3.5 billion. Combined ratio expanded 150 bps to 86.5%.<br><br><strong>North America Personal P&amp;C Insurance</strong>: Net premiums written slipped 2% year over year to $1.3 billion. Combined ratio improved 170 bps to 90.3%.<br><br><strong>North America Agricultural Insurance</strong>: Net premiums written increased 20.1% year over year to $466 million. Looking at earnings over the last twelve months, <strong>Cincinnati Financial has a P/E ratio of 14.98</strong>. In other words, at today\'s prices, investors are paying $14.98 for every $1 in prior year profit. </p> \n<p> <span class="veryHighlightLink"> <a href="https://simplywall.st/stocks/us/insurance/nasdaq-cinf/cincinnati-financial?utm_medium=finance_user&amp;utm_source=yahoo&amp;utm_campaign=CTA_ticker&amp;blueprint=795807"> View our latest analysis for Cincinnati Financial </a> </span> </p> \n<h3> How Do You Calculate Cincinnati Financial\'s P/E Ratio? </h3> \n<p> The <strong>formula for P/E</strong> is: </p> \n<p> Price to Earnings Ratio = Share Price  Earnings per Share (EPS) </p> \n<p> Or for Cincinnati Financial: </p> \n<p> P/E of 14.98 = $112.49  $7.51 (Based on the trailing twelve months to June 2019.) </p> \n<h3> Is A High Price-to-Earnings Ratio Good? </h3> \n<p> The higher the P/E ratio, the higher the price tag of a business, relative to its trailing earnings. That isn\'t a good or a bad thing on its own, but a high P/E means that buyers have a higher opinion of the business\'s prospects, relative to stocks with a lower P/E. </p> \n<h3> Does Cincinnati Financial Have A Relatively High Or Low P/E For Its Industry? </h3> \n<p> One good way to get a quick read on what market participants expect of a company is to look at its P/E ratio. As you can see below Cincinnati Financial has a P/E ratio that is fairly close for the average for the insurance industry, which is 15.7. </p> \n<figure> \n <a href="https://simplywall.st/stocks/us/insurance/nasdaq-cinf/cincinnati-financial?utm_medium=finance_user&amp;utm_source=yahoo&amp;utm_campaign=Infographic&amp;blueprint=795807#PE-PEG-gauge" target="_blank"> <img src="https://s.yimg.com/uu/api/res/1.2/RtOw.xxEXhto7q9SsaOqeg--/YXBwaWQ9eXRhY2h5b247cT03NTs-/https://media.zenfs.com/en/simply_wall_st__316/272c434c78be87a7c737da72fbc426ff" alt="NasdaqGS:CINF Price Estimation Relative to Market, September 3rd 2019"> </img></a> \n <figcaption>\n  NasdaqGS:CINF Price Estimation Relative to Market, September 3rd 2019\n </figcaption> \n</figure> \n<p> Its P/E ratio suggests that Cincinnati Financial shareholders think that in the future it will perform about the same as other companies in its industry classification. The company could surprise by performing better than average, in the future. Further research into factors such as <strong><a href="https://simplywall.st/stocks/us/insurance/nasdaq-cinf/cincinnati-financial?utm_medium=finance_user&amp;utm_source=yahoo&amp;blueprint=795807#insider_trading" target="_blank">insider buying and selling</a></strong>, could help you form your own view on whether that is likely. </p>\n<h3>How Growth Rates Impact P/E Ratios</h3> \n<p> Generally speaking the rate of earnings growth has a profound impact on a company\'s P/E multiple. When earnings grow, the \'E\' increases, over time. And in that case, the P/E ratio itself will drop rather quickly. Then, a lower P/E should attract more buyers, pushing the share price up. </p> \n<p> Cincinnati Financial increased earnings per share by a whopping 32% last year. And it has bolstered its earnings per share by 23% per year over the last five years. With that performance, I would expect it to have an above average P/E ratio. </p>\n<h3> Remember: P/E Ratios Don\'t Consider The Balance Sheet </h3> \n<p> It\'s important to note that the P/E ratio considers the market capitalization, not the enterprise value. Thus, the metric does not reflect cash or debt held by the company. The exact same company would hypothetically deserve a higher P/E ratio if it had a strong balance sheet, than if it had a weak one with lots of debt, because a cashed up company can spend on growth. </p> \n<p> Such spending might be good or bad, overall, but the key point here is that you need to look at debt to understand the P/E ratio in context. </p> \n<h3> So What Does Cincinnati Financial\'s Balance Sheet Tell Us? </h3> \n<p> Cincinnati Financial\'s net debt is 0.1% of its market cap. The market might award it a higher P/E ratio if it had net cash, but its unlikely this low level of net borrowing is having a big impact on the P/E multiple. </p> \n<h3> The Verdict On Cincinnati Financial\'s P/E Ratio </h3> \n<p> Cincinnati Financial\'s P/E is 15 which is below average (17.3) in the US market. The EPS growth last year was strong, and debt levels are quite reasonable. The low P/E ratio suggests current market expectations are muted, implying these levels of growth will not continue. </p> \n<p> Investors should be looking to buy stocks that the market is wrong about. If the reality for a company is not as bad as the P/E ratio indicates, then the share price should increase as the market realizes this.   'content': '<p>Momentum investing is all about the idea of following a stock\'s recent trend, which can be in either direction. In the \'long\' context, investors will essentially be "buying high, but hoping to sell even higher." And for investors following this methodology, taking advantage of trends in a stock\'s price is key; once a stock establishes a course, it is more than likely to continue moving in that direction. The goal is that once a stock heads down a fixed path, it will lead to timely and profitable trades.</p>\n<p>Even though momentum is a popular stock characteristic, it can be tough to define. Debate surrounding which are the best and worst metrics to focus on is lengthy, but the Zacks Momentum Style Score, part of the Zacks Style Scores, helps address this issue for us.</p>\n<p>Below, we take a look at <b>Cincinnati Financial (CINF)</b>, which currently has a Momentum Style Score of B. We also discuss some of the main drivers of the Momentum Style Score, like price change and earnings estimate revisions.</p>\n<p>It\'s also important to note that Style Scores work as a complement to the Zacks Rank, our stock rating system that has an impressive track record of outperformance. Cincinnati Financial currently has a Zacks Rank of #2 (Buy). Our research shows that stocks rated Zacks Rank #1 (Strong Buy) and #2 (Buy) and Style Scores of A or B outperform the market over the following one-month period.</p>\n<p>You can see the current list of Zacks #1 Rank Stocks here &gt;&gt;&gt;</p>\n<p><b>Set to Beat the Market?</b></p>\n<p>In order to see if CINF is a promising momentum pick, let\'s examine some Momentum Style elements to see if this insurer holds up.</p>\n<p>A good momentum benchmark for a stock is to look at its short-term price activity, as this can reflect both current interest and if buyers or sellers currently have the upper hand. It\'s also helpful to compare a security to its industry; this can show investors the best companies in a particular area.</p>\n<p>For CINF, shares are up 3.5% over the past week while the Zacks Insurance - Property and Casualty industry is up 1.19% over the same time period. Shares are looking quite well from a longer time frame too, as the monthly price change of 2.09% compares favorably with the industry\'s 0.27% performance as well.</p>\n<p>While any stock can see a spike in price, it takes a real winner to consistently outperform the market. Over the past quarter, shares of Cincinnati Financial have risen 10.56%, and are up 45.7% in the last year. On the other hand, the S&amp;P 500 has only moved 0.97% and 3.76%, respectively.</p>\n<p>Investors should also pay attention to CINF\'s average 20-day trading volume. Volume is a useful item in many ways, and the 20-day average establishes a good price-to-volume baseline; a rising stock with above average volume is generally a bullish sign, whereas a declining stock on above average volume is typically bearish. CINF is currently averaging 726,970 shares for the last 20 days.</p>\n<p><b>Earnings Outlook</b></p>\n<p>The Zacks Momentum Style Score encompasses many things, including estimate revisions and a stock\'s price movement. Investors should note that earnings estimates are also significant to the Zacks Rank, and a nice path here can be promising. If you purchase the stock on or after the 3rd of September, you won\'t be eligible to receive this dividend, when it is paid on the 18th of September. </p> \n<p> Everest Re Group\'s upcoming dividend is US$1.40 a share, following on from the last 12 months, when the company distributed a total of US$5.60 per share to shareholders. Calculating the last year\'s worth of payments shows that Everest Re Group has a trailing yield of 2.3% on the current share price of $239.51.
